The murder of Dutch filmmaker Theo van Gogh, a vocal critic of Islam, shocked the nation.
Van Gogh, known for his controversial film "Submission," was shot and stabbed while cycling in Amsterdam.
His collaboration with Ayaan Hirsi Ali, a critic of Islamic culture, led to death threats.
The suspect had ties to extremist Muslims, sparking concerns about societal divisions.
Despite the tragedy, a memorial gathering drew 20,000 people, including Muslims condemning the killing.
Van Gogh's death highlighted the clash between free speech and intolerance in Dutch society, prompting widespread condemnation and calls for unity.
